EDA - Presidential Election Data 2020

Importing Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(usmap)
library(maps)
library(stringr)

Importing the data

  1. dataset data1: This dataset gives the state-wise total registered voters
  2. dataset data2: This dataset gives percentage of voting happened for year 2020 in each county
  3. dataset data3: This dataset gives the total votes received by a presidential candidate in each counties, party of the presidential candidate and a variable showing if he won or lost that county

Exploratory Data Analysis for data1

# Adding the state-wise population in 2020 to the data1

popl <- read.csv("popl.csv")    # importing data
colnames(popl)[colnames(popl) == '..state' ] <- 'state' # Changing the colname

# Joining the popl dataset with data1 by 'state' variable
state_df <- popl %>% left_join(data1, by = 'state') %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  mutate(registered_voter_percent = round((total_votes/popl)*100))  # Finding the percent of registered voters with respect to the total population

str(state_df)

Visualization for state-wise population

Lets see how the population is distributed state-wise and find the state with highest population.

Through the the visualization we can say that California, Texas, Florida and New York are the states with highest population

# Statewise population visualization

usmap::plot_usmap(data = state_df, values = "popl", color = "red", labels = TRUE) +
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "white", high = "red", name = "") +
  theme(legend.position = "right") + labs(title = "State-wise population")

state_df %>% arrange(desc(popl)) %>%
  slice(., n = 1:10, popl) %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x= reorder(state, popl), y=popl)) + 
              geom_bar(stat='identity', fill = "#EA907C") + labs(x = "State", y = "Population") +
              theme_grey()

Visualization for registered voters percentage

Which are the states with highest percentage of registered voters?

Vermont, New Hampshire, Maine, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Montana, and Colorado are the states with highest percentage of registered voters

# Percentage of registered users
usmap::plot_usmap(data = state_df, values = "registered_voter_percent", labels = TRUE) +
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "light blue", high = "#0053a0", name = "Percent") +
  theme(legend.position = "right") +labs(title = "Pecentage Registered Voters")

state_df %>% arrange(desc(registered_voter_percent)) %>%
  top_n(., 20, registered_voter_percent) %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x= reorder(state, registered_voter_percent), y=registered_voter_percent)) + 
              geom_bar(stat='identity', fill = "steelblue") + 
              theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 7)) + coord_flip() + xlab("") + ylab("Percent Registered Voter")

Exploratory Data Analysis for data2

2020 voter turnout is the highest in over a century. Lets look at the the voter turnout by county

Looking at the percentage of voter turn out by County

Plotting the counties using FIPS

# Voter turnout by county

county_data <- data2 %>% dplyr::select(county, percent, state)   # pulling the required columns
colnames(county_data) <- c("subregion", "percent", "region")     # changing colname for joining tables

# Manipulating the character arrays in the county_data to match with the other table
county_data$subregion <- str_to_lower(county_data$subregion)
county_data$region <- str_to_lower(county_data$region)
county_data$subregion <- str_replace(county_data$subregion, " county", "")

# County map - getting the co-ordinates of the county
county_coord <- map_data("county")

# Joining county map to county_data
county_map <- county_coord %>% left_join(county_data, by = c("subregion", "region"))

sum(is.na(county_map))  # There are 5543 na values i.e the voters turnout for these county is not availabe
## [1] 5543
# Plot
ggplot(county_map, aes(long, lat, group = group)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(fill = percent), color = "black") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low="#c91c1c", high="#90bf5e", mid = "#c91c1c", midpoint = 50) +
  coord_map(projection = "albers", lat0 = 39, lat1 = 45) +
  labs(title = "County wise voter turnout") + 
  theme(legend.position = "right")

# the grey part the regions whose voting data is not yet available

# Total votes received by top two candidates
candidate_vote <- data3 %>% dplyr::select(candidate, total_votes) %>%
  filter(candidate == "Joe Biden" | candidate == "Donald Trump") %>%
  group_by(candidate) %>%
  summarise(total_votes_by_candidate = sum(total_votes)) %>%
  arrange(desc(total_votes_by_candidate))

Votes received by presidential candidates statewise:

# Votes received by Joe Biden and Donald Trump in each state
candidate_vote1 <- data3 %>% 
  dplyr::select(candidate, total_votes,state) %>%
  filter(candidate == "Joe Biden" | candidate == "Donald Trump") %>%
  group_by(candidate, state) %>% 
  na.omit() %>%
  summarise(total_by_candidate = sum(total_votes))

# Plotting 
ggplot(data = candidate_vote1, aes(candidate, total_by_candidate, fill = candidate)) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~ state)

Percent votes received by candidates:

Candidates other then Joe Biden and Donald Trump are under Others category

votes_rec <- data3 %>% 
  dplyr::select(state, candidate, party, total_votes) %>%
  mutate(., Updated_candidate = ifelse(candidate == "Joe Biden" | candidate == "Donald Trump", candidate, "Other")) %>% group_by(Updated_candidate) %>% arrange(desc(total_votes))
  
votes_rec$candidate = NULL
  
total_votes <- votes_rec %>% summarise(candidate_total = sum(total_votes))

slices <- c(total_votes$candidate_total)
lbls <- c(total_votes$Updated_candidate)
pct <- round(slices/sum(slices)*100)
lbls <- paste(lbls, pct)
lbls <- paste(lbls,"%",sep="")
pie(slices, lbls, main = "Percent votes by candidate", col=colors(length(lbls)))

Percent Votes received by Joe Biden in all state

vote_joe <- data3 %>% dplyr::select(state, candidate, total_votes) %>%
  filter(candidate == "Joe Biden")  %>%
  group_by(state) %>%
  summarise(total_joe = sum(total_votes)) %>% 
  left_join(data1, by = "state") %>%
  mutate(joe_percent = round((total_joe/total_votes)*100))

usmap::plot_usmap(data = vote_joe, values = "joe_percent", labels = TRUE) +
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "white", high = "#1167b1", limits = c(20, 100), name = "Percent") + 
  theme(legend.position = "right") + labs(title = "Biden's vote across all state")

Percent Votes received by Donald Trump in all state

vote_trump <- data3 %>% dplyr::select(state, candidate, total_votes) %>%
  filter(candidate == "Donald Trump")  %>%
  group_by(state) %>%
  summarise(total_donald = sum(total_votes)) %>% 
  left_join(data1, by = "state") %>%
  mutate(donald_percent = round((total_donald/total_votes)*100))

usmap::plot_usmap(data = vote_trump, values = "donald_percent", labels = TRUE) +
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "white", high = "#CB454A", limits = c(20, 100), name = "Percent") + 
  theme(legend.position = "right") + labs(title = "Trump's vote across all state")

Win by county

# Filtering to find the candidate that won in each county
county_win <- data3 %>% dplyr::select(state, county, candidate, won) %>%
  filter(won == TRUE) %>%
  arrange(state, county)

# Changing colnames to match fips data
colnames(county_win) <- c("region","subregion", "candidate", "won")

# String Manipulation
county_win$region <- str_to_lower(county_win$region)
county_win$subregion <- str_to_lower(county_win$subregion)
county_win$subregion <- str_replace(county_win$subregion, " county", "")

# Joining the table
county_map2 <- county_coord %>% left_join(county_win, by = c("subregion", "region"))
